    Author:
    Parisbre56 The ordinal of the status codes are exchanged between the various servers and clients to indicate various things
    TO ENSURE COMPATIBILITY BETWEEN OLDER AND NEWER VERSIONS, NEW STATUS CODES MUST ALWAYS BE PUT AT THE END OF THIS LIST, OTHERWISE THEY WILL CHANGE THE ORDINAL OF OLDER STATUS CODES.

      VALUE_OUT_OF_BOUNDS
      Sent to indicate that the provided data was out of bounds.

      • SET_REFRESH_RATE

        public static final StatusCode SET_REFRESH_RATE
        Sent by the client during registration to inform the server about the MAXIMUM time it is going to wait before refresh requests.
        Followed by an integer that represents the time in seconds. Should be greater than 0.
        Note that refresh requests may be sent more often than that.
        The server will consider the client to have timed out and essentially be disconnected some time after REFRESH_RATE seconds pass. The client can reconnect with either a NAME_REGISTRATION_REQUEST or a REFRESH_REQUEST.

      • EXIT_REQUEST

        public static final StatusCode EXIT_REQUEST
        Informs the server that the client is exiting and should be marked as disconnected.
        Note that clients marked as disconnected can not reconnect via refresh requests,

      • INTERFACE_ADDRESS_DECLARATION

        public static final StatusCode INTERFACE_ADDRESS_DECLARATION
        Sent to declare a new interface address as part of sending interface statistics data
        Usually followed by the interface address in the form of the length an IP byte array (NOT A STRING ONE!!) followed by the array itself. A size of zero indicates null, which means the capture was made with no known interface address.
        Followed by string pattern or ip pattern malicious activity declarations
